    <text id="R1551003T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Confederate Secretary of War Judah P. Benjamin writes General William Loring,
                    stationed at Staunton, in December, 1861, to discuss the movement of his
                    command.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    WAR DEPARTMENT, C. S. A.,
                    <name type="recipient">Brig. Gen. W. W. LORING, Staunton:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1861-12-23">December 23, 1861.</date>
                        <name type="place">Richmond,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>SIR:</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Your letters of the 13th instant and 17th instant have been received, and the
                    measures taken by you in disposing and moving your forces meet the entire
                    approval of the Department.</p>
                <p>You will use your own discretion as to the proper force to be left under command
                    of Col. (now Brig. Gen. ) E. Johnson, and of the length of time it will be
                    proper to hold the pass which the enemy has made so disastrous an effort to
                    force.</p>
                <p>I inclose you a letter for Brig.-Gen. Johnson, knowing that it cannot but be
                    agreeable to you conveyed to meritorious and gallant soldiers under your
                    command.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>I am, your obedient servant,</salute>
                    <signed>J. P. BENJAMIN,<lb/> Secretary of War.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
